direct_answer.text: Heavy rainfall leads to lowered friction between car tires and the road surface because the presence of standing water reduces the contact points available for traction. When compared to driving on dry roads, vehicles require longer stopping distances since the reduced friction hampers immediate brake force transfer needed to halt motion efficiently. Additionally, drivers may experience delayed reactions time — slower reflex responses to changing road conditions cause them to react later than optimal moments required to prevent collisions effectively.
